04759nam a22006255i 9780292756953DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927569537 a10.7560/7569462doi  a(DE-B1597)586458  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF2230.1.R3bB76 2014 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a299.811/442231 aBrosseder, Claudia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Power of Huacas :bChange and Resistance in the Andean World of Colonial Peru /cClaudia Brosseder. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. A Land Obsessed with Confessions; or, The Historians’ Insights into the World of Colonial Andean Religious Specialists -- tChapter Two. Civil Versus Ecclesiastical Authorities -- tChapter Three. The Sickening Powers of Christianity: A Response by Andean Religious Specialists -- tChapter Four. Talking to Demons: The Intensified Persecut ion of Andean Religious Specialists (ca. 1609–1700) -- tChapter Five. From Out spoken Criticism to Clandestine Resistance -- tChapter Six. Glimpses of the Protective Powers of Andean Rituals in the Highlands -- tChapter Seven. Andean Notions of Nature and Harm, and the Disempowerment of Andean Healers -- tChapter Eight. Weeping Statues: The End of Jesuit Demonology and the Survival of an Andean Culture -- tChapter Nine. Epilogue -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tConsulted Archives -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe role of the religious specialist in Andean cultures of the sixteenth, seventeenth, and eighteenth centuries was a complicated one, balanced between local traditions and the culture of the Spanish. In The Power of Huacas, Claudia Brosseder reconstructs the dynamic interaction between religious specialists and the colonial world that unfolded around them, considering how the discourse about religion shifted on both sides of the Spanish and Andean relationship in complex and unexpected ways. In The Power of Huacas, Brosseder examines evidence of transcultural exchange through religious history, anthropology, and cultural studies. Taking Andean religious specialists—or hechizeros (sorcerers) in colonial Spanish terminology—as a starting point, she considers the different ways in which Andeans and Spaniards thought about key cultural and religious concepts. Unlike previous studies, this important book fully outlines both sides of the colonial relationship; Brosseder uses extensive archival research in Bolivia, Chile, Ecuador, Peru, Spain, Italy, and the United States, as well as careful analysis of archaeological and art historical objects, to present the Andean religious worldview of the period on equal footing with that of the Spanish. Throughout the colonial period, she argues, Andean religious specialists retained their own unique logic, which encompassed specific ideas about holiness, nature, sickness, and social harmony. The Power of Huacas deepens our understanding of the complexities of assimilation, showing that, within the maelstrom of transcultural exchange in the Spanish Americas, European paradigms ultimately changed more than Andean ones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruxReligion. 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruxRites and ceremonies. 0aShamanismzPeru. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292756953423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292756953/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_